e participants would occasionally see notifications from their occasionally occasionally. They would occasionally see notifications from their most used phones phone apps appear on their computer screen. One group was told that their smartphones were actually signed signed signed the computer. How? Is it? Synced. Synced. Okay. Synced to the computer. One group was told that their smartphones were actually synced to the computer. So they believed that the notifications they got on the computer were real and personal. The next group was told that any notification they saw were for someone else. And the last group''s notifications were blurred, so they would see a pop out pop up, but couldn''t read any information. The researchers found that just one notification of any type could slow down a participant''s cognitive processing for around seven seconds, slowing the action time on the stroke tasks. But the effect was particularly strong among those who fought fought. They were they were seeing fought fought. Who those who fought, they were seeing notifications from their own phone. And the more they wanted to check a notification and the stronger the emotional response, the more, the more, their reaction time was delayed. Seven sec might not seem like a lot. However, Hippologt Fournier, one of the study authors told CPOST, Even short disruption when repeated dose dozens or hundreds of time per day may meaningfully affect concentration and", "confidence": 0.99609375, "words": [{"word": "hi", "start": 1.12, "end": 1.8399999, "confidence": 0.98413086, "punctuated_word": "Hi."}, {"word": "hello", "start": 1.8399999, "end": 3.12, "confidence": 0.9133301, "punctuated_word": "Hello?"}, {"word": "hey", "start": 6.8799996, "end": 7.3599997, "confidence": 0.7907715, "punctuated_word": "Hey."}, {"word": "great", "start": 7.3599997, "end": 7.8399997, "confidence": 0.98461914, "punctuated_word": "Great."}, {"word": "great", "start": 7.8399997, "end": 8.16, "confidence": 0.9946289, "